citeinfo.origin: Spatial Analysis Center - Yellowstone National Park
citeinfo.title: All Roads in Yellowstone National Park

descript.abstract: This data set contains all the roads in Yellowstone National Park (YNP) and includes service roads, residential roads and roads within developed areas. The roads are represented by line segments with attributes attached to them. Attributes include: type, surface, speed limit, the date that the road segment was surveyed and the surveyor's name, type of survey, full name, alternate name, and functional classification. Data was obtained either by heads- up digitizing using 1- Meter or less DOQQS, 7.5' USGS DRGs, Federal Highways surveys or using a differentially corrected GPS. Original survey completed in 1997, roads are updated and corrected as needed.
descript.purpose: This data set was developed in order to establish an accurate record of all the roads in YNP. This data set replaces a previous data set that was developed by heads up digitizing off 15' DRGS.

attracc.attraccr: For the original road survey, each attribute in the data set was checked for accuracy by driving all the roads. Subsequent errors or changes were entered into the attribute table and queried for quality assurance.

dataqual.logic: All arcs contain topology. All unnecessary node errors were removed and all intersecting arcs were snapped together. The coverage was built and cleaned in January of 2000. Transferred to file geodatabase structure in 2009. Topology verified after edits.

horizpa.horizpar: Horizontal accuracy reflect the survey method. Arcs digitized off the DOQQs and DRGs have a horizontal accuracy of 12.19 meters. Sub-meter accuracy is possible for arcs obtained by a GPS survey.

procstep.procdesc: Road segments were either heads-up digitized off georeferenced 7.5 minute DRGs and 1 meter DOQQs or surveyed using a differential GPS unit (Trimble Pro XL or Pro XR). PDOP maximum was set to 6, and data were only collected when at least 4 satellites were readable. GPS information was corrected using base station files from the Idaho Falls Community Base Station (ftp.inel.gov/pub/gps) and Pathfinder Office software. Editing was done in an Arc/Info environment.
Edited GPS data in Arc/Info. Manually snapped arcs to intersecting arcs. Eliminated all unnecessary node errors. Assigned attributes to each arc.

procstep.procdesc:
Dataset imported to file geodatabase structure. Following fields were added to conform to NPS enterprise GIS data standards: FeatureID, GeometryID, UnitCode, Name, AltName, ShortName, IsExtant, IsSensitive, FNotes, FCategory, MapMethod, MapSource, SourceDate, EditDate, HError, VError.
Upon further inspection, noted that the CLASS/CATEGORY fields were not correct - they should agree, such as Class I = Principle Park Roads, Class 2 = Connector Park Roads, etc. Checked literature (K:\Infrastructure_FMSS\Roads\Documents\ NPSParkRoadStandards1984.pdf) and 1998 Road Inventory for Yellowstone National Park (binders) and found the correct classification table (K:\Infrastructure_FMSS\Roads\Documents\ GENERAL PARK ROAD FUNCTIONAL CLASSIFICATION.doc)
Calculated MapMethod, MapSource, and SourceDate fields from SURVEY field Selection - principle park roads or class = 1 - all OK Selection - connector park roads or class = 2 - made corrections Selection - special purpose park roads or class = 3 - all OK Selection - primitive park roads or class = 4 - made corrections Selection - Administrative Access roads or class = 5 - made corrections Selection - Restricted roads or class = 6 - made corrections Calculated "CLASS" field to "RoadClass" field Calculated "CATEGORY" field to "RoadClassText" field Calculated "RoadAccess" field as "Public Road" where RoadClass=1,2,3, or 4 Calculated "RoadAccess" field as "Administrative Road" where RoadClass=5 or 6 Archived changes Deleted "CLASS" "CATEGORY" "SURVEY" fields as they were redundant - the original fields were saved in the archive copy

overview.eaover:
All the road segments of Yellowstone National Park were surveyed. Arcs were defined by speed limit segments and intersections.
The Name of each road segment was obtained by using the 1985 Road Classification Report.
RoadClassText is the functional road classification system defined by the 1985 Road Classification Report. The RoadClass is a number that corresponds to road classification. There are eight possible categories (below).
GENERAL PARK ROAD FUNCTIONAL CLASSIFICATION TABLE
Class 1 (I) - Principal Park Road/Rural Parkway (Public Roads): Roads which constitute the main access route, circulatory tour, or thoroughfare for park visitors. Route umbers 1-99. Note: Rural Parkways (e.g. Natchez Trace) are numbered 1-9. All other FC 1 routes have two digit numbers.
Class 2 (II) - Connector Park Road (Public Roads): Roads which provide access within a park to areas of scenic, scientific, recreational or cultural interest, such as overlooks, campgrounds, etc. Route Numbers 100-199.
Class 3 (III) - Special Purpose Park Road (Public Roads): Roads which provide circulation within public areas, such as campgrounds, picnic areas, visitor center complexes, concessionaire facilities, etc. These roads generally serve low-speed traffic and are often designed for one-way circulation. Route Numbers 200-299.
Class 4 (IV) - Primitive Park Roads (Public Roads): Roads which provide circulation through remote areas and/or access to primitive campgrounds and undeveloped areas. These roads frequently have no minimum design standards and their use may be limited to specially equipped vehicles. Route Numbers 200-299. Note: Functional Classes III and IV have the same route numbers because, historically, they were numbered similarly.
Class 5 (V) - Administrative Access Road (Administrative Roads): All public roads intended for access to administrative developments or structures such as park offices, employee quarters, or utility areas. Route Numbers 400-499.
Class 6 (VI) - Restricted Road (Administrative Roads): All roads normally closed to the public, including patrol roads, truck trails, and other similar roads. Route Numbers 400-499. Note: Functional Classes V and VI have the same route numbers because historically they were numbered similarly and often there is little distinction between these routes. For example, because utility areas and employee housing are often closed to the public, this restriction would result in classification of FC VI rather than FC V.
Class 7 (VII) - Urban Parkway (Urban Parkways and City Streets): These facilities serve high volumes of park and non-park related traffic and are restricted, limited-access facilities in an urban area. This category or roads primarily encompasses the major parkways which serve as gateways to our nation's capital. Other major park roads or portions thereof, however, may included in this category. Route Numbers 1-9.
Class 8 (VIII) - City Streets (Urban Parkways and City Streets): City streets are usually extensions of the adjoining street system that are owned and maintained by the National Park Service. The construction and/or reconstruction should conform with accepted local engineering practice and local conditions. Route Numbers 600-699.

attr.attrdef: Internal feature number.

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: Feature geometry.
SURFACE denotes if the road is paved or dirt
SPEED contains the speed limit of the road segment in miles per hour (15, 25, 35, 45,55)
contains the name of the surveyor
SURVEY_DATE relates the date the survey information was collected

The TYPE attribute defines the road use status. Roads can either be used for primary, secondary or tertiary travel. Unsure from where this rating comes. Was included in the original data layer, so remains for the time being.
Facilities Management Software System unique identifier for the road segment. Work was completed by matching FMSS database entries to roads layer.
a unique identifier for the feature (physical entity). Auto-generated by NPS "Generate GUID" utility

a unique identifier for the geospatial representation (geometry). Using the NPS Buildings data standard as an example, GeometryID would be equivalent to the Geometry_ID. In the case where a Building is represented by a center point and a perimeter polygon, the point and polygon would have distinct and unique values for GeometryID, and would have identical values for FeatureID. Auto-generated by NPS "Generate GUID" utility

The NPS standard alphabetic abbreviation for the NPS unit with which the data is associated. Data not specifically associated with an NPS Unit will use the value WASO. Data come from the UnitCode domain.
The full name of the feature.
Specifies whether or not the feature (physical entity) currently exists.
A field to provide comments or notes for a feature.
a text value used to define the "Feature Category". Each data standard will have a specific domain (list of values).
The method used to create the spatial data. Domain Values are: Heads up Digitized; Tablet Digitized; Differential GPS; Autonomous GPS; Derived/Calculated; Conventional Survey; Other; Unknown
The estimated error on the horizontal plane that exists in the spatial data depending on the MapMethod. This field is most applicable to data created by GPS. The Default Value is Unknown
The estimated error on the vertical plane that exists in the spatial data depending on the MapMethod. This field is most applicable to data created by GPS. The Default Value is Unknown
Data source used to create the spatial depending on the MapMethod. (Ex. NAIP Imagery)
The date of the map source (i.e. MapSource) used to create the spatial data.
The date that the spatial data was created, if not known, the date that it was loaded into an implementation model.
Text field to provide notes for a geometry record (point, polygon or line).
Class code for the road taken from the "General Park Road Functinal Classification Table" Roman numerals changed to Arabic for sorting purposes.
Access type (public or administrative)for the road taken from the "General Park Road Functinal Classification Table"
